This paper discusses the training of generative adversarial networks (GANs), which are commonly used in machine learning for image generation and other tasks. The paper specifically focuses on the discriminator component of GANs, which is essentially a binary classifier that distinguishes between real and generated samples. As a result, the paper is likely to be relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), neural networks (cs.NE), and statistical learning (cs.SD).
